segments.text: In the early evening hours, just as it began to darken, she lit the lamp above the armchair in the corner, where she was accustomed to nestle engrossed in the book she was reading.

Suddenly, the front door was pushed open, and in the doorway stood a young man, quite handsome, with exceptionally smooth and light hair, dressed in a sporty elegance, and everything about him suggested he was from abroad.
He was surprised to see her curled up in the armchair and smiled at her with an embarrassed smile.
She jumped up and stood immediately.
Hi, she said.
Hi, he replied, continuing in English with a slight foreign accent.
Am I in the right place?
I was told I could get a good beer here and maybe something to eat.
She smiled.
You'll have a beer in a moment, but I'll need to arrange something to eat for you after you decide what exactly you want.
As they walked inside towards the bar, she turned on the rest of the lights.
He looked around and commented that the paintings on the walls were very beautiful, stopping in front of the blue one and gazing at it for a long time.
Strange, she thought to herself.
He immediately found her painting.
The one Lucy always said Joseph must have been drunk when he painted it.
But there's nothing like it.
Do you know Israeli beer?
There's Goldstar and Maccabee.
What do you prefer?
You choose for me, he asked.
She slowly poured him some Goldstar, tilting the beer glass so that foam wouldn't form, just as Joseph had taught her.
I can make you a roast beef sandwich with mustard and some vegetables, or if you'd like, an omelet and salad with bread and cheese.
He smiled at her, looking at her gently.
Do you run this place on your own?
How old are you?
No, she answered.
My dad runs it, but he's not always around, so I'm here.
It's actually a pension with guest rooms, not just a restaurant and bar, and I'm almost 18.
I'll go for the roast beef, he said.
She made her way to the kitchen behind the wall.
The place is charming, he thought to himself.
It has the intimacy of a home, and it feels familiar.
And this girl, so calm and straightforward.
She enters a conversation so naturally.
How is she not afraid to be here alone?
She returned from the kitchen and placed two sandwiches before him, garnished with vegetables and a small dish of pickles and olives.
He felt the hunger come over him and immediately bit into the first sandwich.
It's very tasty, he smiled.
I hear a slight accent in your English.
Where are you from?
From Switzerland, from a town called Winterthur.
I'm a textile machinery engineer and came to set up the entire new line at Paul Gatt in Kiriat Gatt.

I've been here almost a month and today, when I was sitting with the CEO, I told him I was missing a small place to have a beer and he laughed and said, but there's the pink house in front of you and there's nothing better than it.
Now I see he was right.
She smiled a sad smile.
The place used to be much busier with people, but since my mom passed away about a year and a half ago, things have been a bit sluggish.
Sorry to hear about your mom, but for me, it's good enough, very pleasant and clean here.
And the paintings on the walls are very beautiful, especially the blue one.
Those are paintings by my dad," she said proudly.
And the portrait above you is of my mom.
My name is Rolf.
And I'm Lyora," she smiled.
And so, without realizing it, with great delicacy and intimacy that slowly wove between them, they found themselves speaking of their lives.
He about distance Switzerland and other countries he had been to,
and she about her Ashkelon, especially about Aphrodar.
How it was built from nothing on the sand dunes thanks to Jewish philanthropists from South Africa and what is particularly worth seeing there and her upcoming enlistment in the army.
Occasionally she poured him more beer until he asked for black coffee like he had at work.
When they were done, she looked up and saw it was already 11.30.
Enough for today, he said to her, reached out his hand.
And pressed hers warmly.
It was very pleasant and very tasty.
You're a very special girl.
I'll be back.
And he indeed returned almost every day.
Sometimes he met another guest or two and chatted with them.
But mostly they were alone, talking about their souls, their lives.
Only days later did he meet Joseph, who immediately said to him, I've heard about you.
Nice to meet you.
He laughed at him and shook his hand.
I'm taking care of the girl for you.
He said, sending her a warm glance.
It was the first time she understood that what was being woven between them was not just friendship.
It was intimacy between a man and a woman.
That look, as if it was a secret between them, the way he looked into her blue eyes, warm-flooded her body, and she returned his smile, quietly, without a word.
Two weeks later, suddenly he stopped coming, and she found herself sitting and waiting for him to walk in.
Every evening, as it began to darken, she would turn her gaze towards the front door, hoping that in just a moment it would be pushed open and he would enter.
Within herself, she admitted that she missed him.
For a moment, she thought maybe he traveled, but somehow she was sure he wouldn't have left without saying goodbye.

Then, one evening, just like on the first night, as it began to darken and the streetlights hadn't yet been lit, the front door was pushed open and there he stood, smiling gently and watching her with excitement.
I missed you so much.
He spread his arms wide as if inviting her towards him.
In a second, she found herself embraced in his arms as if it was where she had always belonged.
He held her face and gently kissed her forehead, moving to her cheek, slowly finding her lips.
So gently, as if he was afraid something would break, he realized she was experiencing something new, different, letting her get used to it and feeling she was fully surrendering.
That gentle kiss turned into something powerful, channeling through both their lips all the feelings that had been growing between them over the weeks.
He gently moved her face slightly away, o' me for a moment to look deeply into her eyes.
God, I missed you.
She responded very touched.
Me too.
For a moment I thought you had left.
No, I was at the factory up north for a week.
Only there did I realize how much I missed you.
How hard it is for me without you.
How did you get into my heart like that?"
he asked with a smile.
With the beer, she replied with a warm smile.
She didn't know herself.
She had never been kissed like that, never felt her whole body tremble at someone's touch.
There had only been the games among teenagers, holding hands or slow dancing closely at parties, and also a kiss with closed lips that she didn't quite enjoy.

But that's what everyone did, and even that was very little, and here came her dream night, and he was handsome with such blue eyes, and his fair hair was very soft, and when he looked at her or spoke to her, he exuded warmth and wisdom and maturity, and a gentle humor that filtered into a sentence and made it funny.
He wasn't a boy.
He was a man.
And she knew she could rest her head on his shoulder and relax.
Only this desire that spread through her body with surprise and joy was entirely new to her.
And she gave it freedom, kissing without recognition, caressing, petting, sinking into his eyes.
Finally, they half sat, half sank into the armchair in the corner, cuddled together, and she rested her head on his shoulder.
She always knew that the boys her age didn't interest her that much.
Something in the way she grew up, facing the bigger world, having to mature early due to Lucy's illness and death, created a maturity gap between her and them.
She knew something about life that most kids her age were still far from, but it wasn't just a knowledge gap.
Also, living in a household with Bohemian parents, who raised her with great freedom and trusted her common sense, as Joseph would say, I have a child with common sense.
And so her love for prose books, poetry, and the good old music, she had two very close friends, like brothers, soulmates.
Both were almost three years older than her.
Boys, not girls, but she didn't have boy-boy friends.
although there were some who tried and didn't interest her.
There was only one episode, with the cultural coordinator at the health fund's convalescent home, who also sang and played the guitar.
One evening he saw her on the lawn, then sought her out until he reached the pink house and began courting her, captivating her with stories and talks about books and poetry and music.
With him, she actually caressed for the first time, kissed a bit, but not beyond that.
It was quite strange because he was 24, a university student.
What did he even find in her that he didn't find in the older women who swirled around him?
When he left, he wrote her love letters that spanned entire pages.
In the end, it dwindled into a warm friendship, and she would meet him from time to time when she studied in Tel Aviv.
The whole story with him happened when she was not yet sixteen.
It was a very emotionally loaded time due to Lucy's illness, and now she understood that she couldn't focus on him or what he might have brought into her life then.
He was also the first to compliment her appearance.
She didn't think she was beautiful at all.
Maybe just her eyes.

She was a bit boyish, tall and slender, her hair long and straight, sometimes loose, sometimes braided, always in jeans and a t-shirt, barefoot almost until winter, loved dogs, rode horses when possible, played the piano by ear, read voraciously, recited poetry books by heart.
She didn't engage too much in beautification, and yet, slowly inside her, her femininity began to mature.
But what she felt now, cuddled and curled up in Ralph's arms, was something different and new.
Perhaps it was the beginning of love.
The song Misty, which she loved so much, described what it feels like when you miss someone so much.
even if they're gone for just a few days, when you love their scent and warm hands and what is reflected in their eyes when they look deeply into yours.
Look at me, helpless like a kitten up a tree, feeling like I'm cleaning to a cloud, I'm misty, holding your hand.
She always knew she would feel this way when it would come.
He held her chin and lifted her head to him.
What will be with us?"
he asked.
I'm finishing here in a few months and going back home, right after you enlist.
Nothing has even happened between us, and I already can't bear the thought of being far from you.

He went on to describe his hometown and the weather, so different because it's mostly cold and snowy there, but the landscape is amazing as if he were trying to check with her if she'd be willing to live in such a place, without realizing it.
She tilted the conversation towards the amazing landscapes.
I've never been abroad, but the books I read make me familiar with so many places.
I close my eyes and can see streets and mountains and waterfalls in my lion's eye, as if I'm there.
I've been to so many countries.
Each time the company sends me to assemble and operate the textile machines it manufactures.
He was then 27, nearly a decade older than her.
Presumably he had known quite a few women.

Yet she felt they were melting into each other, hands reaching out, exploring, caressing, embracing, and a mouth finding hidden nooks and corners of her neck, his neck, and his hand seeking hidden places.
She did not recoil, something in the way he embraced her instilled a sense of safety that he wanted what was best for her.
She felt intense warmth flood her loins and clumped to him eagerly.
Then he distanced her face slightly, stroking it.
as if trying to cool things off from moving further.
He was the one who gently led them, slowing down tenderly, and she trusted him, laying her head on his shoulder in silence, once more enveloped in the words of Misty.
You can say that you're leading me on, but it's just what I want you to do.
Don't you notice how helplessly I'm lost?
That's why I'm following you.
Slowly, her eyes closed and exhausted from the storm of her emotions.
She fell asleep in his lap.
